# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fleet-management
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fleet-management/electronic-logging-device] An **electronic logging device** (**ELD** or **E-Log**) is a piece of electronic hardware attached to a commercial motor vehicle engine to record driving hours.
[src:fleet-management/electronic-logging-device] The driving hours of commercial drivers (truck and bus drivers) are typically regulated by a set of rules known as the hours of service (HOS) in the United States and as drivers' working hours in Europe.
[src:fleet-management/electronic-logging-device] The Commercial Vehicle Driver Hours of Service Regulations vary in Canada and the United States.
[src:fleet-management/electronic-logging-device] An ELD monitors a vehicle’s engine to capture data on whether the engine is running, whether the vehicle is moving, distance driven, and duration of engine operation.
[src:fleet-management/electronic-logging-device] AOBRD (Automatic On-Board Recording Device) was the first in history with an appearance in 1988.
[src:fleet-management/electronic-logging-device] Then came the paper logs or electronic on-board recorders (EOBR) were used for hours of service tracking.
[src:fleet-management/electronic-logging-device] While recorder logs improve the accuracy of the data, the lack of a consistent data format meant that the logs needed to be regenerated to an equivalent hardware ("paper") format for review and enforcement.
[src:fleet-management/electronic-logging-device] The Record of Duty Status (RoDS) definition within the ELD legislation provides a consistent format for enforcement personnel to review, so the ELD Mandate was created.
[src:fleet-management/electronic-logging-device] The Federal Motor Carrier Safety Administration (FMCSA) announced the Final Rule of the ELD mandate, and ELD regulations being implemented in several phases with a compliance date of December 18, 2017.
[src:fleet-management/electronic-logging-device] Fleets already equipped with loggers or recorders had until December 2019 to ensure compliance with the published specifications.
[src:fleet-management/electronic-logging-device] Before the final rule of the ELD mandate was announced, fleets used the Automatic On-Board Device (AOBRD), a much simpler version of the ELD device that did not provide fleets with many features.
[src:fleet-management/electronic-logging-device] For instance, ELDs provide a standardized format and transfer process for roadside inspections, have more sophisticated location tracking, and enable drivers to accept or reject edits made to their driving logs – all of which are required under the ELD mandate.
[src:fleet-management/electronic-logging-device] As mentioned before, it became mandatory for fleets to transition from AOBRDs to ELDs.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] These functions can be dealt with by either an in-house fleet-management department or an outsourced fleet-management provider.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] The number of light duty vehicles registered in commercial fleets in Europe as of 2016 was 15 million, and 19.5 million in North America.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] Even with these record numbers of registration, light duty vehicles represent only 62% of all fleet sales.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] The range of functions involved in fleet management are highly interrelated and generally integrated.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] While some services and products can be engaged separately, an overall system that integrates the data from various functions is required for optimal performance.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] Vehicle tracking systems provide a number of data points regarding engine diagnostics, driving behaviors, and geo-location.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] But there are a multitude of other data points outside of vehicle tracking systems that significantly impact fleet performance.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] The more specialized functions a fleet performs, the more systems and data points are involved in integration.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] A key component in fleet management systems, is the vehicle tracking component.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] This component is usually GPS-based, but sometimes it can be based on GLONASS or a cellular triangulation platform.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] Once vehicle location, direction and speed are determined from the GPS components, additional tracking capabilities transmit this information to a fleet management software application.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] Methods for data transmission include both terrestrial and satellite.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] Satellite tracking communications, while more expensive, are critical if vehicle tracking is to work in remote environments without interruption.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] Users can see actual, real-time locations of their fleet on a map.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] This is often used to quickly respond on events in the field.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] In the European Union, the Data Act, which came into application in September 2025, requires manufacturers of connected vehicles to provide fleet operators with access to vehicle-generated data, enabling integration with third-party fleet management platforms.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] An advanced fleet management systems (FMS) can connect to the vehicle's onboard computer, and gather data for the user.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] Data such as mileage and fuel consumption are gathered into a global statistics scheme.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] Highly developed fleet management and vehicle telematics systems collect a full range of data in real-time and for transport and fleet managers.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] By combining received data from the vehicle tracking system and the on-board computer, it is possible to form a profile for any given driver (average speed, frequency of detours, breaks, severity of manoeuvres, choice of gears, etc.).
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] This data can be used to highlight drivers with dangerous habits and to suggest remedial training applicable to the issues, or to ensure that drivers are meeting KPIs.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] Fleet management apps have shown to reduce driving incidents.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] Geofencing, a key feature in many fleet management and vehicle telematics systems, significantly boosts asset security.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] It works by creating a virtual geographic boundary around a specific location using mapping technology.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] When a GPS-enabled device or asset tracker enters or exits this pre-defined area, it triggers an automated alert, which users can receive via text, email, or push notification.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] This functionality allows for proactive monitoring and immediate response to unauthorized movements.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] Fleet management software enables people to accomplish a series of specific tasks in the management of any or all aspects relating to a company's fleet of vehicles.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] These specific tasks encompass all operations from vehicle acquisition to disposal.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] Software, depending on its capabilities, allows functions such as recording driver and vehicle details, the tracking of procurement costs, scheduling of maintenance and servicing tasks, import of fuel transactions, route optimization, and measuring of fleet performance via reports and charts.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] Fleet management also refers to the management of ships while at sea.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] Shipping fleet management contracts are normally given to fleet management companies that handle aspects like crewing, maintenance, and day-to-day operations.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] This gives the ship owner time to concentrate on cargo booking.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] Recent advances in fleet management allow for the addition of over-the-air (OTA) security and control of fleet vehicles.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] Fleet Security and Control includes security of the vehicle while stopped or not in operation and the ability to safely disable a vehicle while in operation.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] This allows the fleet manager to recover stolen or rogue vehicles while reducing the chance of lost or stolen cargo.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] The additional of Fleet Security and Control to a fleet management system gives a fleet card manager preventative measures to address cargo damage and loss.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] Remote vehicle disabling systems provide users at remote locations the ability to prevent an engine from starting, prevent movement of a vehicle, and to stop or slow an operating vehicle.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] Remote disabling allows a dispatcher or other authorized personnel to gradually decelerate a vehicle by downshifting, limiting the throttle capability, or bleeding air from the braking system from a remote location.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] Some of these systems provide advance notification to the driver that the vehicle disabling is about to occur.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] After stopping a vehicle, some systems will lock the vehicle's brakes or will not allow the vehicle's engine to be restarted within a certain time-frame.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] Remote disabling systems can also be integrated into a remote panic and emergency notification system.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] In an emergency, a driver can send an emergency alert by pressing a panic button on the dashboard, or by using a key-fob panic button if the driver is within close proximity of the truck.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] Then, the carrier or other approved organization can be remotely alerted to allow a dispatcher or other authorized personnel to evaluate the situation, communicate with the driver, and/or potentially disable the vehicle.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] The timely replacement of vehicles and equipment is a process that requires the ability to predict asset lifecycles based on costing information, utilization, and asset age.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] Organizations prefer to use new fleet as a strategy for cost reduction where the used fleet is sold so that a new fleet is maintained.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] Funding requirements are also an issue, because many organizations, especially government, purchase vehicles with cash.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] The ad hoc nature and traditional low funding levels with cash has put many operations in an aged fleet.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] This lack of adequate funding for replacement can also result in higher maintenance costs due to aged vehicles.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] In the UK, in April 2008, the Corporate Manslaughter Act was strengthened to target company directors as well as their drivers in cases of road deaths involving vehicles used on business.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] The Police have said they now treat every road death as 'an unlawful killing' and have the power to seize company records and computers during their investigations.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] They will bring prosecutions against company directors who fail to provide clear policies and guidance for their employees driving at work.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] Unfortunately, in the UK a number of businesses are failing to meet their duty of care.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] In particular prosecutions can be brought against company directors for failing to meet their duty of care and allowing HGV driver hours to exceed the legal limits.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] Failure to comply with EU rules can result in a fixed penalty of up to £300, a graduated deposit of up to £1500 or you could be summoned to court.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] Directors and business owners may not be aware that privately owned vehicles used for business journeys are treated exactly the same as company owned vehicles.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] Directors have an equal responsibility under the law to ensure these vehicles are also roadworthy and correctly insured.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] It is vital that every company has a 'Driving at Work' policy in place covering every element of their business vehicle operation, no matter how few vehicles are involved and who owns them.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] Every employee driving for business is required to sign up to the policy.
[src:fleet-management/fleet-management] In this way, the directors can reduce the risk of being prosecuted and a possible custodial sentence.
[src:fleet-management/fuel-management-systems] A **fuel-management system** is an integrated technology solution combining hardware and software to monitor, control, and report on fuel consumption and inventory.
[src:fleet-management/fuel-management-systems] These systems are used in industries that rely on transportation or powered machinery, including road and rail transport, shipping, aviation, and construction.
[src:fleet-management/fuel-management-systems] The primary purpose of a fuel management system is to reduce operational costs, prevent gasoline theft, and improve the overall efficiency of a fleet of vehicles or equipment.
[src:fleet-management/fuel-management-systems] For many fleets, fuel is one of the largest operating costs after depreciation, making its effective management an important business function.
[src:fleet-management/fuel-management-systems] The technology is applied in two main contexts.
[src:fleet-management/fuel-management-systems] The first is managing on-site fuel dispensing, where the system controls access to private fuel pumps at a depot.
[src:fleet-management/fuel-management-systems] The second, a more modern approach, involves vehicle-centric monitoring using a vehicle tracking system.
[src:fleet-management/fuel-management-systems] In this context, a telematics device on the vehicle collects data directly from the engine to track real-world fuel consumption, providing detailed insights for fleet management.
[src:fleet-management/fuel-management-systems] Additives can substantially improve performance, especially under adverse storage conditions or challenging climatic environments.
[src:fleet-management/fuel-management-systems] A fuel management system integrates several key hardware and software components to create a comprehensive solution.
[src:fleet-management/fuel-management-systems] The hardware components are the physical devices used to secure, dispense, and track fuel, and can be categorized by whether they are installed at a fixed fueling site or on a mobile asset.
[src:fleet-management/fuel-management-systems] The industry consists of many specialized hardware manufacturers whose products are often integrated into larger software platforms.
[src:fleet-management/fuel-management-systems] These components are installed on the vehicles or equipment being refueled.
[src:fleet-management/fuel-management-systems] The software platform is the central hub where all data collected by the hardware is aggregated and analyzed.
[src:fleet-management/fuel-management-systems] FMS software can be deployed as a standalone platform centered exclusively on fuel, or as a module within a larger platform for fleet digitalization, such as Fleetmatics or Wialon.
[src:fleet-management/fuel-management-systems] In the latter case, fuel management is one function within a comprehensive fleet telematics system, alongside other features like a vehicle tracking module, maintenance scheduling, and driver management.
[src:fleet-management/fuel-management-systems] The primary purpose of a fuel management system is to provide businesses with precise control over their fuel consumption, a significant variable cost in fleet operations.
[src:fleet-management/fuel-management-systems] A core function is to secure fuel inventory and prevent unauthorized access.
[src:fleet-management/fuel-management-systems] By requiring authentication at the pump, the system ensures only authorized personnel and vehicles can dispense fuel, reducing the risk of gasoline theft.
[src:fleet-management/fuel-management-systems] When combined with telematics data, the system can also detect siphoning by flagging discrepancies between fuel levels recorded by vehicle sensors and the amount of fuel dispensed.
[src:fleet-management/fuel-management-systems] The system creates a detailed digital record of every fueling transaction, allowing managers to analyze fuel economy.
[src:fleet-management/fuel-management-systems] This detailed monitoring helps identify vehicles with poor fuel efficiency that may require maintenance, or drivers who could benefit from eco-driving training.
[src:fleet-management/fuel-management-systems] For organizations with bulk fuel storage, the system automates inventory management.
[src:fleet-management/fuel-management-systems] Using automated tank gauging (ATG) sensors, the software provides a real-time view of fuel stock levels and can quickly flag any losses that could indicate a leak or theft from the storage tank itself.
[src:fleet-management/fuel-management-systems] The data generated by a fuel management system is often integrated with a broader fleet management software platform.
[src:fleet-management/fuel-management-systems] This allows businesses to combine fuel consumption data with other operational metrics, such as vehicle location data, driver behavior, and maintenance records.
[src:fleet-management/fuel-management-systems] Integrating this information provides a comprehensive view of a vehicle's total cost of ownership (TCO), enabling more informed strategic decisions.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] A **GPS tracking unit**, commonly referred to as a **GPS tracker** or simply a **tracker**, is a device used as part of a tracking system to track the location of the asset it is connected to.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] It uses a Global Navigation Satellite System (GNSS) to determine its geographic position.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] This location data, along with other vehicle or asset telemetry, is transmitted to an Internet-connected device or a central server using an embedded cellular, radio, or satellite modem.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] This enables the real-time monitoring and management of vehicles, assets, personnel and animals from a remote location, and is used in intelligent transportation systems.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] The global market was valued at over $2.5 billion in 2022 and projected to grow at a CAGR of over 13% to reach $4.76 billion by 2027.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] GPS tracking units are used by consumers and are a component of fleet telematics systems and fleet digitalization.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] Data collected by these devices is typically sent to specialized fleet management software platforms.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] While many modern vehicles are equipped with a factory-installed telematic control unit (TCU) from the manufacturer, aftermarket GPS tracking units are used to manage mixed fleets (with vehicles from different brands) and to equip vehicles that lack native telematics systems.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] Specialized hardware manufacturers produce these devices.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] A modern GPS tracking unit integrates several key electronic components to determine and transmit its location and other data.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] GPS tracking units can be categorized by their primary application and form factor.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] While most modern devices transmit their location in real-time (a function known as data "pushing"), some specialized units may only log their position history for later download (data "logging").
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] The main distinction is between devices designed for personal/asset use and those designed for vehicle integration.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] Personal and asset trackers are typically small, portable, battery-powered devices designed to track people, animals, or high-value mobile assets.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] Their compact size allows them to be carried, attached to equipment, or fitted to a pet's collar.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] Vehicle trackers are devices designed for installation in vehicles such as cars, trucks, motorcycles, buses for public transport, and heavy machinery.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] The commercial vehicle segment is the largest end-user of GPS tracking devices, driven by the need for real-time fleet monitoring and management.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] These devices are a core component of modern fleet management systems and are often referred to as automatic vehicle location (AVL) systems.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] The global market for this hardware is served by numerous specialized manufacturers, with companies like CalAmp, ORBCOMM, Queclink, and Teltonika among the leading suppliers.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] Hardwired trackers are wired directly into a vehicle's electrical system, providing a constant and reliable power source.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] This installation allows for deep integration, enabling the tracker to monitor ignition status, control a starter interrupt for vehicle immobilization, and connect to a wide range of third-party sensors to monitor variables such as fuel level, cargo temperature, and tire pressure.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] They can often connect directly to the vehicle's CAN bus to read detailed operational data.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] This type is most commonly used in professional fleet digitalization for commercial vehicles.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] OBD plug-in trackers are designed for simple installation by connecting directly into a vehicle's OBD-II port.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] This connection method requires no special tools.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] In addition to providing location data, OBD trackers can read a wide range of diagnostic information from the onboard computer, including engine RPM, fuel level, and Diagnostic Trouble Codes (DTCs), which are useful for maintenance purposes.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] Battery-powered trackers are self-contained, wireless devices that operate on their own long-life batteries.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] This design provides flexibility in placement, as they can be attached to any vehicle or asset without requiring wiring.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] They are often used for tracking non-powered assets like trailers and containers, or for covert security applications.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] The use of GPS tracking units is widespread across commercial, governmental, and personal applications.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] While the technology is the same, the implementation and goals vary significantly by use case.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] The largest application for GPS tracking units is in the commercial sector, where devices are installed in vehicles and equipment to provide real-time data to a central software platform.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] In commercial fleet management, GPS tracking is a key component of fleet digitalization.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] These systems are also crucial for security, helping to prevent gasoline theft and providing data for comprehensive fuel-management systems.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] GPS tracking is a core technology in modern precision agriculture, used to improve the efficiency and productivity of farm operations.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] This application involves placing battery-powered trackers on mobile assets that are non-powered or intermittently powered.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] A primary use for both consumers and businesses is vehicle security, a vertical often referred to as stolen vehicle recovery (SVR).
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] In this application, a covertly installed tracker provides the vehicle's location to the owner or law enforcement in the event of a theft.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] The demand for SVR solutions is particularly strong in regions and emerging markets where vehicle crime rates are a significant problem.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] Some systems, like LoJack, are specifically designed for vehicle recovery.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] Compact, battery-powered trackers are widely used for personal safety.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] The use of GPS tracking is regulated by laws that vary significantly by jurisdiction.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] The legal framework generally balances the right to monitor one's own property with an individual's right to privacy.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] Key legal considerations often depend on who is performing the tracking (government vs. private citizen) and whether the person being tracked has given consent.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] In the European Union, the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) is the primary law governing GPS tracking.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] Under GDPR, location data is considered **personal data**, meaning its collection and processing require a valid legal basis.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] In the United States, the law distinguishes between government use and private use of GPS trackers.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] The use of GPS trackers by law enforcement is limited by the Fourth Amendment to the United States Constitution.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] United States*, the Supreme Court ruled that accessing historical cell-site location information (CSLI) constitutes a Fourth Amendment search, and thus generally requires a warrant.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] This ruling built upon the 2012 case *United States v.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] Jones*, which held that attaching a GPS tracker to a suspect's vehicle also constitutes a search requiring a warrant.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] The use of GPS trackers by private citizens is regulated at the state level, and many states have specific laws against electronic surveillance without consent.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] For example, California Penal Code Section 637.7 makes it a misdemeanor to use an electronic tracking device to determine the location or movement of a person, with an exception for when the owner of the vehicle has consented.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] Other laws related to stalking, harassment, and invasion of privacy may also apply.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] Laws in other countries often follow similar principles.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] In Australia, for example, the use of tracking devices is regulated by state-level workplace surveillance acts, such as the Workplace Surveillance Act 2005 in New South Wales, which generally require that employees be notified that tracking is in place.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] In August 2010, Brazilian company Unilever ran an unusual promotion where GPS trackers were placed in boxes of Omo laundry detergent.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] Teams would then track consumers who purchased the boxes of detergent to their homes where they would be awarded a prize for their purchase.
[src:fleet-management/gps-tracking-unit] The company also launched a website (in Portuguese) to show the approximate location of the winners' homes.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] Pathfinding is closely related to the shortest path problem, within graph theory, which examines how to identify the path that best meets some criteria (shortest, cheapest, fastest, etc) between two points in a large network.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] At its core, a pathfinding method searches a graph by starting at one vertex and exploring adjacent nodes until the destination node is reached, generally with the intent of finding the cheapest route.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] Although graph searching methods such as a breadth-first search would find a route if given enough time, other methods, which "explore" the graph, would tend to reach the destination sooner.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] An analogy would be a person walking across a room; rather than examining every possible route in advance, the person would generally walk in the direction of the destination and only deviate from the path to avoid an obstruction, and make deviations as minor as possible.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] Two primary problems of pathfinding are (1) to find a path between two nodes in a graph; and (2) the shortest path problem—to find the optimal shortest path.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] Basic algorithms such as breadth-first and depth-first search address the first problem by exhausting all possibilities; starting from the given node, they iterate over all potential paths until they reach the destination node.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] These algorithms run in $O(|V|+|E|)$ , or linear time, where V is the number of vertices, and E is the number of edges between vertices.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] The more complicated problem is finding the optimal path.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] The exhaustive approach in this case is known as the Bellman–Ford algorithm, which yields a time complexity of $O(|V||E|)$ , or quadratic time.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] However, it is not necessary to examine all possible paths to find the optimal one.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] Algorithms such as A* and Dijkstra's algorithm strategically eliminate paths, either through heuristics or through dynamic programming.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] By eliminating impossible paths, these algorithms can achieve time complexities as low as $O(|E|\log(|V|))$ .
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] The above algorithms are among the best general algorithms which operate on a graph without preprocessing.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] However, in practical travel-routing systems, even better time complexities can be attained by algorithms which can pre-process the graph to attain better performance.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] One such algorithm is contraction hierarchies.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] A common example of a graph-based pathfinding algorithm is Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] This algorithm begins with a start node and an "open set" of candidate nodes.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] At each step, the node in the open set with the lowest distance from the start is examined.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] The node is marked "closed", and all nodes adjacent to it are added to the open set if they have not already been examined.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] This process repeats until a path to the destination has been found.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] Since the lowest distance nodes are examined first, the first time the destination is found, the path to it will be the shortest path.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] Dijkstra's algorithm fails if there is a negative edge weight.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] In the hypothetical situation where Nodes A, B, and C form a connected undirected graph with edges AB = 3, AC = 4, and BC = −2, the optimal path from A to C costs 1, and the optimal path from A to B costs 2.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] Dijkstra's Algorithm starting from A will first examine B, as that is the closest.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] It will assign a cost of 3 to it, and mark it closed, meaning that its cost will never be reevaluated.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] Therefore, Dijkstra's cannot evaluate negative edge weights.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] However, since for many practical purposes there will never be a negative edgeweight, Dijkstra's algorithm is largely suitable for the purpose of pathfinding.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] A* is a variant of Dijkstra's algorithm with a wide variety of use cases.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] A* assigns a weight to each open node equal to the weight of the edge to that node plus the approximate distance between that node and the finish.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] This approximate distance is found by the heuristic, and represents a minimum possible distance between that node and the end.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] This allows it to eliminate longer paths once an initial path is found.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] If there is a path of length x between the start and finish, and the minimum distance between a node and the finish is greater than x, that node need not be examined.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] A* uses this heuristic to improve on the behavior relative to Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] When the heuristic evaluates to zero, A* is equivalent to Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] As the heuristic estimate increases and gets closer to the true distance, A* continues to find optimal paths, but runs faster (by virtue of examining fewer nodes).
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] When the value of the heuristic is exactly the true distance, A* examines the fewest nodes.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] In many applications (such as video games) this is acceptable and even desirable, in order to keep the algorithm running quickly.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] Pathfinding has a history of being included in video games with moving objects or NPCs.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] Chris Crawford in 1982 described how he "expended a great deal of time" trying to solve a problem with pathfinding in *Tanktics*, in which computer tanks became trapped on land within U-shaped lakes.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] "After much wasted effort I discovered a better solution: delete U-shaped lakes from the map", he said.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] The concept of hierarchical pathfinding predates its adoption by the video game industry and has its roots in classical artificial intelligence research.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] One of the earliest formal descriptions appears in Sacerdoti's work on ABSTRIPS (Abstraction-Based STRIPS) in 1974, which explored hierarchical search strategies in logic-based planning.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] Later research, such as Hierarchical A* by Holte et al., further developed the theory of abstraction hierarchies in search problems.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] In the context of video games, the need for efficient planning on large maps with limited CPU time led to the practical implementation of hierarchical pathfinding algorithms.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] A notable advancement was the introduction of Hierarchical Path-Finding A* (HPA*) by Botea et al. in 2004.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] HPA* partitions the map into clusters and precomputes optimal local paths between entrance points of adjacent clusters.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] At runtime, it plans an abstract path through the cluster graph, then refines that path within each cluster.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] This significantly reduces the search space and allows for near-optimal planning with much faster performance.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] Partial-Refinement A* (PRA*), developed by Sturtevant and Buro, takes a similar approach but emphasizes interleaved planning and acting.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] Instead of refining the entire path immediately, PRA* refines only the first few steps and continues refining the rest as needed during execution.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] This is especially useful in dynamic environments.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] Similar techniques include navigation meshes (navmesh), used for geometric planning in games, and multimodal transportation planning, such as in variations of the travelling salesman problem that involve multiple transport types.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] A hierarchical planner performs pathfinding in two phases: first, between clusters at a high level; then, within individual clusters at a low level.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] This structure enables guided local search with fewer nodes, resulting in high performance.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] The main drawback is the implementation complexity of maintaining abstraction layers and refinements.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] A map with a size of 3000×2000 nodes contains 6 million tiles.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] Planning a path directly on this scale, even with an optimized algorithm, is computationally intensive due to the vast number of graph nodes and possible paths.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] A hierarchical approach divides the map into 300×200 node clusters, forming a 10×10 grid (100 clusters total).
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] The high-level abstract graph now contains only 100 nodes.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] A path is planned between these clusters, which is computationally cheap.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] Once the abstract path is found, each cluster on the path is processed using a regular A* planner to find the exact low-level route within.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] This two-stage process significantly improves efficiency while maintaining near-optimal path quality.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] Multi-agent pathfinding is to find the paths for multiple agents from their current locations to their target locations without colliding with each other, while at the same time optimizing a cost function, such as the sum of the path lengths of all agents.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] Many multi-agent pathfinding algorithms are generalized from A*, or based on reduction to other well studied problems such as integer linear programming.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] However, such algorithms are typically incomplete; in other words, not proven to produce a solution within polynomial time.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] Some parallel approaches, such as Collaborative Diffusion, are based on embarrassingly parallel algorithms spreading multi-agent pathfinding into computational grid structures, e.g., cells similar to cellular automata.
[src:fleet-management/route-optimization] A different category of algorithms sacrifice optimality for performance by either making use of known navigation patterns (such as traffic flow) or the topology of the problem space.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] The term *telematics* is a translation of the French word *télématique,* which was first coined by Simon Nora and Alain Minc in a 1978 report to the French government on the computerization of society.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] It referred to the transfer of information over telecommunications and was a portmanteau blending the French words *télécommunications* ("telecommunications") and *informatique* ("computing science").
[src:fleet-management/telematics] The original broad meaning of telematics continues to be used in academic fields, but in commerce it now generally means vehicle telematics.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] Telematics is closely related to, and largely built upon, the concept of telemetry.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] While telemetry refers specifically to the remote measurement and transmission of data (widely used in fields such as aerospace, meteorology, medicine, and defense), telematics incorporates telemetry but extends it with telecommunications, informatics, and integration into digital platforms.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] In modern usage, the term *telematics* is applied mainly in commercial contexts, with dominant applications in the vehicular, personal, and asset domains (see Key applications).
[src:fleet-management/telematics] While the term telematics is broad, its modern usage is dominated by a number of key applications in the vehicular context, as well as for personal and asset tracking.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] The largest commercial application of telematics is in fleet management, often utilizing a comprehensive Fleet telematics system.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] Telematics devices are used as the primary data collection tool for fleet digitalization, enabling businesses to manage their fleets of cars, trucks, and other assets.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] In volatile economic climates, telematics is a key tool for reducing high operational costs, especially for fuel.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] Beyond fleet vehicles, telematics is widely used in the form of small, portable, battery-powered trackers for a diverse range of personal and asset monitoring applications.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] Video telematics is an evolution of traditional telematics that integrates cameras, such as a Dashcam, with telematics data.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] This adds visual context to events, which is used for proactive driver coaching using AI, accident reconstruction, and insurance claim validation.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] Usage-based insurance is a model where auto insurance premiums are directly correlated with real-time driving behavior.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] A telematics device in the vehicle monitors metrics such as distance driven, speed, and braking force.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] Safer drivers are often rewarded with lower premiums.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] Telematics technology is integral to modern carsharing and ride-hailing services like Uber, Lyft, and Zipcar.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] The onboard device allows the company to track the vehicle's location, monitor its usage, and manage remote locking and unlocking for users, who typically access the service via a smartphone app.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] Telematics is used in modernizing public transport.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] It enables real-time vehicle tracking, which provides passengers with accurate arrival and departure times through mobile apps and station displays.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] It also helps transport authorities with route optimization, schedule adherence monitoring, and efficient dispatching.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] Telematics systems facilitate safety communications.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] Vehicle manufacturers increasingly use embedded telematics to offer connected services to consumers, often through a smartphone app.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] These services include automotive navigation systems, sometimes called a Journey planner, remote vehicle control (e.g., remote start or locking doors), vehicle health reports, and concierge services.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] The Association of Equipment Management Professionals (AEMP) developed the industry's first telematics standard.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] In 2008, AEMP brought together the major construction equipment manufacturers and telematics providers in the heavy equipment industry to discuss the development of the industry's first telematics standard.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] Following agreement from Caterpillar, Volvo CE, Komatsu, and John Deere Construction & Forestry to support such a standard, the AEMP formed a standards development subcommittee chaired by Pat Crail CEM to develop the standard.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] This committee consisted of developers provided by the Caterpillar/Trimble joint venture known as Virtual Site Solutions, Volvo CE, and John Deere.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] This group worked from February 2009 through September 2010 to develop the industry's first standard for the delivery of telematics data.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] The result, the AEMP Telematics Data Standard V1.1, was released in 2010 and officially went live on October 1, 2010.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] As of November 1, 2010, Caterpillar, Volvo CE, John Deere Construction & Forestry, OEM Data Delivery, and Navman Wireless are able to support customers with delivery of basic telematics data in a standard xml format.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] Komatsu, Topcon, and others are finishing beta testing and have indicated their ability to support customers in the near future.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] The AEMP's telematics data standard was developed to allow end users to integrate key telematics data (operating hours, location, fuel consumed, and odometer reading where applicable) into their existing fleet management reporting systems.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] As such, the standard was primarily intended to facilitate importation of these data elements into enterprise software systems such as those used by many medium-to-large construction contractors.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] One option available to machine owners was to visit multiple websites to manually retrieve data from each manufacturer's telematics interface and then manually enter it into their fleet management program's database.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] This option was cumbersome and labor-intensive.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] A second option was for the end user to develop an API (Application Programming Interface), or program, to integrate the data from each telematics provider into their database.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] This option was quite costly as each telematics provider had different procedures for accessing and retrieving the data and the data format varied from provider to provider.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] This option automated the process, but because each provider required a unique, custom API to retrieve and parse the data, it was an expensive option.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] In addition, another API had to be developed any time another brand of machine or telematics device was added to the fleet.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] A third option for mixed-fleet integration was to replace the various factory-installed telematics devices with devices from a third party telematics provider.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] Although this solved the problem of having multiple data providers requiring unique integration methods, this was by far the most expensive option.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] In some cases, these devices are limited to location and engine runtime, although they are increasingly able to accommodate a number of add-on sensors to provide additional data.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] The AEMP Telematics Data Standard provides a fourth option.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] The current draft version of the AEMP Telematics Data Standard is now called the AEM/AEMP Draft Telematics API Standard, which expands the original standard Version 1.2 to include 19 data fields (with fault code capability).
[src:fleet-management/telematics] This new draft standard is a collaborative effort of AEMP and the Association of Equipment Manufacturers (AEM), working on behalf of their members and the industry.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] This Draft API replaces the current version 1.2 and does not currently cover some types of equipment, e.g., agriculture equipment, cranes, mobile elevating work platforms, air compressors, and other niche products.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] In addition to the new data fields, the AEM/AEMP Draft Telematics API Standard changes how data is accessed in an effort to make it easier to consume and integrate with other systems and processes.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] To achieve a globally recognized standard for conformity worldwide, the AEM/AEMP Draft Telematics API Standard will be submitted for acceptance by the International Organization for Standardization (ISO).
[src:fleet-management/telematics] Final language is dependent upon completion of the ISO acceptance process.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] In 2007, a project entitled the European Automotive Digital Innovation Studio (EADIS) was awarded 400,000 Euros from the European Commission under its Leonardo da Vinci program.
[src:fleet-management/telematics] EADIS used a virtual work environment called the Digital Innovation Studio to train and develop professional designers in the automotive industry in the impact and application of vehicle telematics so they could integrate new technologies into future products within the automotive industry.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] A **vehicle tracking system** is a type of tracking system that combines a hardware device installed in a vehicle, typically a GPS tracking unit, with a software platform to monitor its location and collect a wide range of operational data in near real-time.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] It is a component of fleet digitalization.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] While the primary function of these systems is to provide automatic vehicle location, they also gather data for more advanced applications.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] The location and operational data captured by a tracking system is gathered through Telemetry for modern telematics and comprehensive fleet management platforms.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] These advanced systems use tracking data as a starting point, integrating it with other vehicle and business information to provide features such as predictive maintenance, driver behavior analysis (Driver scoring), and route optimization.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] In fleet operations that use vehicles from different manufacturers, comprehensive solutions are developed to collect and manage this varied data in a single system.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] While common in commercial fleets, this technology is also used in many consumer services, including carsharing and ride-hailing services like Uber or Bolt.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] The scope of modern systems has expanded beyond location monitoring to focus on improving safety, efficiency, and reducing the total cost of ownership (TCO).
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] A vehicle tracking system integrates three main components: hardware to collect data, software to interpret and display it, and a connectivity network to transmit it.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] The hardware component is a physical device, often called a GPS tracking unit or telematics device, installed in the vehicle.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] Its primary function is to collect data about the vehicle's location and operational status.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] In India, SIM-based vehicle tracking is widely deployed for road freight logistics as it requires no hardware installation — platforms cover millions of trucks by querying mobile network location signals via TRAI-compliant APIs.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] Common hardware form factors include hardwired devices connected directly to the vehicle's power supply, plug-and-play OBD trackers, and battery-powered devices for assets like trailers or containers.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] The software component processes raw data from the hardware into usable information.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] Software platforms in this industry are often categorized into two main business models.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] Some solutions are sold as a *bundled* hardware and software package from a single provider, such as those from Geotab or Mix Telematics, where the software is exclusively designed to work with the company's own devices.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] In contrast, other platforms are *device-agnostic*, such as Wialon, meaning they are designed to be compatible with a wide variety of tracking devices from different hardware manufacturers.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] The software consists of a backend server that processes the data and frontend applications that allow users to interact with it.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] The backend is a central server responsible for communicating with the tracking devices.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] Its primary functions are to securely receive the large volumes of data transmitted by the fleet, process it, and store it in a database.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] This server handles tasks like parsing location coordinates, sensor readings, and diagnostic codes, making the information ready for use by frontend applications.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] The frontend is what the user interacts with.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] Common features across these applications include live maps, historical route playback, alerts, and performance dashboards.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] Tracking data is often integrated with other software systems.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] The backend server typically provides an API (Application Programming Interface) that allows for the automated sharing of data with other platforms.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] This enables companies to feed vehicle location, mileage, and usage data directly into their ERP, accounting, payroll, or maintenance software, streamlining workflows and eliminating manual data entry.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] Connectivity links the hardware in the vehicle to the software platform.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] Vehicle tracking technology is utilized across a vast range of commercial and private sectors.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] The global market for commercial vehicle telematics is expanding rapidly, valued at over $85 billion in 2024 and projected to grow to more than $150 billion by 2028.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] The market is led by several major international players, including Geotab, Gurtam, Verizon Connect, and MiX Telematics.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] The market shows distinct regional distributions in its installed base of active systems.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] Europe and North America are the most mature markets, with an estimated 25.5 million and 30.1 million active units respectively at the end of 2023.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] Significant growth is also occurring in emerging markets.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] Latin America is projected to grow to 16.6 million active units by 2029, while Southeast Asia had over 2.7 million active systems at the end of 2023 and is expected to reach 5.4 million by 2028.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] Vehicle tracking technology has been adapted for a wide range of uses, from standard features in consumer cars to critical components of large-scale commercial and regulatory systems.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] Many vehicle manufacturers and aftermarket providers offer tracking systems directly to consumers.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] Governments worldwide mandate the use of vehicle tracking for regulatory and compliance purposes across various sectors.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] These systems are used to ensure that commercial vehicles adhere to laws regarding road usage, safety, and taxation.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] Vehicle tracking is the technological basis of modern Mobility-as-a-Service (MaaS) platforms.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] Services like carsharing and ride-hailing services (e.g., Uber, Bolt, Cabify) rely on real-time tracking for their core functionality.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] The technology enables these platforms to match passengers with the nearest available driver, provide customers with real-time arrival estimates, calculate fares, and monitor driver behavior.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] The most extensive application of vehicle tracking is within commercial fleet management, where the technology serves as a critical tool for improving operational efficiency, enhancing safety, and reducing costs, such as through fuel management and prevention of Gasoline theft.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] The implementation of these systems can deliver a return on investment by enabling greater control over a company's mobile assets.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] The widespread adoption of vehicle tracking systems raises significant privacy concerns, particularly in the context of employee monitoring and government surveillance.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] For commercial fleets, the technology provides employers with the ability to monitor driver behavior, location, and working hours in detail.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] While this is used to enhance safety and efficiency, it has also led to debates over the extent of employee privacy in the workplace.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] In the context of law enforcement, the use of GPS trackers for surveillance has been the subject of major legal challenges.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] In the United States, the landmark Supreme Court case *United States v.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] Jones* (2012) established that placing a GPS tracker on a suspect's vehicle without a warrant constitutes an unlawful search under the Fourth Amendment.
[src:fleet-management/vehicle-tracking-system] This and subsequent rulings have begun to define the legal boundaries for the use of tracking technology by government agencies.
